30006069@@@@@@Background:@@@@1@1@ntucle-docid:213; ntucle-sid:1448@LMC@2019-06-15
30006070@@@@@@Haze has been an annual problem that costs the health of citizens of South East Asia countries, especially Malaysia & Singapore.@@@@1@21@ntucle-docid:213; ntucle-sid:1449@LMC@2019-06-15
30006071@@@@@@Every year, open burning in certain areas causes haze, making the air quality in Malaysia & Singapore drop to unhealthy level.@@@@1@21@ntucle-docid:213; ntucle-sid:1450@LMC@2019-06-15
30006072@@@@@@The irritating smell, disturbed vision and tiny particles in the air impact our life directly.@@@@1@15@ntucle-docid:213; ntucle-sid:1451@LMC@2019-06-15
30006073@@@@@@Haze affect our respiratory system as well as our circulatory system, especially people who are already afflicted with potentially fatal illness such as asthma and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD).@@@@1@30@ntucle-docid:213; ntucle-sid:1452@LMC@2019-06-15
30006074@@@@@@Haze also affect our economics.@@@@1@5@ntucle-docid:213; ntucle-sid:1453@LMC@2019-06-15
30006075@@@@@@For instance, in Singapore, “experts estimated the economic loss caused by the haze to be between S$97.5 million and S$110.5 million” [1].@@@@1@22@ntucle-docid:213; ntucle-sid:1454@LMC@2019-06-15
30006076@@@@@@Problem:@@@@1@1@ntucle-docid:213; ntucle-sid:1455@LMC@2019-06-15
