30006119@@@@@@Trolley: “Stop abusing me!”@@@@1@4@ntucle-docid:214; ntucle-sid:1512@LMC@2019-06-15
30006120@@@@@@Trolley: “Stop abusing me!”@@@@1@4@ntucle-docid:214; ntucle-sid:1516@LMC@2019-06-15
30006121@@@@@@Background@@@@1@1@ntucle-docid:214; ntucle-sid:1517@LMC@2019-06-15
30006122@@@@@@Shopping trolleys are usually provided by retailers to allow customers to easily transport their selected groceries within the store’s vicinity.@@@@1@20@ntucle-docid:214; ntucle-sid:1518@LMC@2019-06-15
30006123@@@@@@However, the prevalence of trolley abuse within Singapore has been rising over the years.@@@@1@14@ntucle-docid:214; ntucle-sid:1519@LMC@2019-06-15
30006124@@@@@@Trolleys were reported to be sighted at locations like housing estates, carparks which are beyond the store’s vicinity.@@@@1@18@ntucle-docid:214; ntucle-sid:1520@LMC@2019-06-15
30006125@@@@@@According to Straits Times, FairPrice alone spends an estimate of $150,000 annually on repairing, replacing and retrieving abandoned trolleys (Min, 2015).@@@@1@21@ntucle-docid:214; ntucle-sid:1521@LMC@2019-06-15
30006126@@@@@@Therefore the issue of trolley abuse is becoming a concern that needs to be addressed immediately.@@@@1@16@ntucle-docid:214; ntucle-sid:1522@LMC@2019-06-15
30006127@@@@@@Problem@@@@1@1@ntucle-docid:214; ntucle-sid:1523@LMC@2019-06-15
30006128@@@@@@The current system to deter trolley abuse by making customers commit to a refundable dollar for usage has proven to be ineffective.@@@@1@22@ntucle-docid:214; ntucle-sid:1524@LMC@2019-06-15
30006129@@@@@@With this system, Sheng Siong lost an average of 38 trolleys each month in the first half of 2013 (Cheong, 2013).@@@@1@21@ntucle-docid:214; ntucle-sid:1525@LMC@2019-06-15
30006130@@@@@@Also, the issue of trolley abuse escalated recently as FairPrice reported that 50 to 150 trolleys were located and retrieved by staff each day (Min, 2015).@@@@1@26@ntucle-docid:214; ntucle-sid:1526@LMC@2019-06-15
30006131@@@@@@This shows that a better solution is needed to curb this issue.@@@@1@12@ntucle-docid:214; ntucle-sid:1527@LMC@2019-06-15
30006132@@@@@@Solution@@@@1@1@ntucle-docid:214; ntucle-sid:1528@LMC@2019-06-15
30006133@@@@@@The proposed solution aims to implement a system comprising trolley cards and barrier gates.@@@@1@14@ntucle-docid:214; ntucle-sid:1529@LMC@2019-06-15
30006134@@@@@@Consumers are required to register for a personalised trolley card which allow them to check out trolley at collaborating retailer stores.@@@@1@21@ntucle-docid:214; ntucle-sid:1530@LMC@2019-06-15
30006135@@@@@@All trolleys will be held and stored behind barrier gates.@@@@1@10@ntucle-docid:214; ntucle-sid:1531@LMC@2019-06-15
30006136@@@@@@There will be two different types of barrier gates.@@@@1@9@ntucle-docid:214; ntucle-sid:1532@LMC@2019-06-15
30006137@@@@@@One to only allow trolleys to be checked out, and another to only allow trolleys to be checked in.@@@@1@19@ntucle-docid:214; ntucle-sid:1533@LMC@2019-06-15
30006138@@@@@@Consumers are required to scan their personalised trolley cards (via NFC) at the barrier gates, in which they will be able to check out the trolley for usage.@@@@1@28@ntucle-docid:214; ntucle-sid:1534@LMC@2019-06-15
30006139@@@@@@For return of trolleys, consumers are required to repeat the same procedure.@@@@1@12@ntucle-docid:214; ntucle-sid:1535@LMC@2019-06-15
30006140@@@@@@A centralise database will keep track of the of the trolley usage which is tagged to an individual.@@@@1@18@ntucle-docid:214; ntucle-sid:1536@LMC@2019-06-15
30006141@@@@@@It will facilitate the retailers to carry out administrative actions (fines) to recover the trolleys.@@@@1@15@ntucle-docid:214; ntucle-sid:1537@LMC@2019-06-15
30006142@@@@@@Fig 1.1 Simple outline of Integrated Trolley System@@@@1@8@ntucle-docid:214; ntucle-sid:1538@LMC@2019-06-15
